==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hay
<hw>Hay</hw> <pr>(h⟦amac⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>hege</ets>: cf. F. <ets>haie</ets>, of German origin. See
<er>Haw</er> a hedge, <er>Hedge</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
hedge.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A net set around the haunt of an animal, especially
of a rabbit.</def> <rj><au>Rowe.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To dance the hay</b></col>, <cd>to dance in a ring.</cd>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hay</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hay
<hw>Hay</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To lay snares for rabbits.</def>
<rj><au>Huloet.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hay</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hay
<hw>Hay</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>hei</ets>, AS.
<ets>h⟦emac⟧g</ets>; akin to D. <ets>hooi</ets>, OHG. <ets>hewi</ets>,
<ets>houwi</ets>, G. <ets>heu</ets>, Dan. & Sw. <ets>h⟦oum⟧</ets>, Icel.
<ets>hey</ets>, <ets>ha</ets>, Goth. <ets>hawi</ets> grass, fr. the root
of E. <ets>hew</ets>. See <er>Hew</er> to cut.]</ety> <def>Grass cut and
cured for fodder.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Make <qex>hay</qex> while the sun shines.</q>
<rj><qau>Camden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Hay</qex> may be dried too much as well as too little.</q>
<rj><qau>C. L. Flint.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hay cap</b></col>, <cd>a canvas covering for a
haycock.</cd> -- <col><b>Hay fever</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>,
<cd>nasal catarrh accompanied with fever, and sometimes with paroxysms
of dyspn⟦oe⟧a, to which some persons are subject in the spring and
summer seasons. It has been attributed to the effluvium from hay, and to
the pollen of certain plants. It is also called <altname>hay
asthma</altname>, <altname>hay cold</altname>, <altname>rose
cold</altname>, and <altname>rose fever</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Hay
knife</b></col>, <cd>a sharp instrument used in cutting hay out of a
stack or mow.</cd> -- <col><b>Hay press</b></col>, <cd>a press for
baling loose hay.</cd> -- <col><b>Hay tea</b></col>, <cd>the juice of
hay extracted by boiling, used as food for cattle, etc.</cd> --
<col><b>Hay tedder</b></col>, <cd>a machine for spreading and turning
new-mown hay. See <er>Tedder</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hay</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Hay
<hw>Hay</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To cut and cure grass for
hay.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

